{"title_page": "Outwood Academy Ripon", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox school \n| name          = Outwood Academy Ripon\n| image         = \n| image_size          = \n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| logo = Fair use logo Outwood Academy Ripon.png \n| motto         = \"Students First\"\n| established   = <!-- {{Start date|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}} -->\n| closed        = \n| type          = [[Academy (English school)|Academy]]\n| admissions    = \n| trust         = \n| religious_affiliation      = \n| president     = \n| head_label    = Principal\n| head          = Gemma Trattles\n| chair_label   = \n| chair         = \n| founder       = \n| medium        = \n| address        = Clotherholme Road\n| location      = \n| city          = [[Ripon]]\n| district      = \n| postcode      = HG4 2DE\n| county        = [[North Yorkshire]]\n| country       = England\n| coordinates   = {{coord|54.1368|-1.5390|type:edu_region:GB_dim:100|format=dec|display=inline,title}}\n| local_authority = [[North Yorkshire County Council|North Yorkshire]]\n| dfeno         = 815/4203\n| urn           = 137412\n| ofsted        = yes\n| staff         = \n| capacity      = 782\n| enrolment    = 656 {{As of|2018|01|lc=on}}\n| gender        = [[Mixed-sex education|Mixed]]\n| lower_age     = 11\n| upper_age     = 18\n| houses        = Africa, Americas, Australasia, Europe\n| colours       = Purple and gold {{color box|#5B3393}} {{color box|#B09C78}}\n| publication   = \n| free_label_1  = \n| free_1        = \n| free_label_2  = \n| free_2        = \n| free_label_3  = \n| free_3        = \n| website       = {{URL|ripon.outwood.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Outwood Academy Ripon''' is a small [[Mixed-sex education|mixed]] [[secondary school]] and [[sixth form]] with [[Academy (English school)|academy status]] situated in the city of [[Ripon]], in [[North Yorkshire]], England.\nIt provides for children ages 11 to 18, and had an enrolment of 656 pupils in 2018.<ref name=\"gias\">{{cite web |title=Outwood Academy Ripon |url=https://get-information-schools.service.gov.uk/Establishments/Establishment/Details/137412 |website=get-information-schools.service.gov.uk |publisher=[[Department for Education]] |accessdate=7 March 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe school is operated by [[Outwood Grange Academies Trust]] and the current principal is Gemma Trattles.<ref name=\"gias\" />\n\nIt is one of over 11 secondary schools in the local area, including nearby selective [[Ripon Grammar School]], and the more distant [[Thirsk School and Sixth Form College]] and Boroughbridge High School.\n\n==History==\nThe school originally opened as a secondary modern in the 1930s. It was known as '''Ripon City School''' from the mid-1990s until 1999, when it became '''Ripon College''',  a [[Community school (England and Wales)|community school]].<ref name=\"gazette-2013\">{{cite news|title=FEATURE: Secondary education in Ripon|url=http://www.ripongazette.co.uk/news/education/feature-secondary-education-in-ripon-1-6328477|accessdate=9 June 2017|work=Ripon Gazette|publisher=Johnston Publishing|date=20 December 2013|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Ripon College|url=http://www.education.gov.uk/edubase/establishment/summary.xhtml?urn=121688|website=EduBase|publisher=[[Department for Education]]|accessdate=9 June 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 2000, teacher James Kelly was a regional winner in the \"Most Outstanding New Teacher\" category of the [[Teaching Awards]].<ref>{{cite news|title=In with a bang|url=http://education.guardian.co.uk/specialreports/teachingawards2000/story/0,,390585,00.html|accessdate=9 June 2017|work=The Guardian|publisher=Guardian News and Media|date=31 October 2000}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2011 Ripon College converted to [[Academy (English school)|academy status]]. It reopened as Outwood Academy Ripon, and became part of [[Outwood Grange Academies Trust]].<ref name=\"gazette-2013\" />\n\nOn 11 November 2015, approximately 40 pupils at the school simultaneously fell ill during an [[Armistice Day]] service. Police said students showed signs of \"sickness and feeling faint sometime between 11:00 and 11.30\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-york-north-yorkshire-34789661|title=School pupils collapse at Outwood Academy in Ripon|publisher=BBC News|date=11 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Pastoral care==\nEach pupil belongs to one of 21 [[tutor group]]s, known as vertical mentor groups (VMGs), which assemble after second lesson and take part in different activities. The mentor groups contain pupils from years 7-11 with the exception of Algeria which is purely Sixth Form.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\n==Special educational needs provision==\nA specialist team of teaching assistants and [[Special education in the United Kingdom|special educational needs]] (SEN) managers work together in 'The Hub' to ensure that students in need of extra support are getting it. Teachers from the Hub will mentor students either on site in the Hub or in the students lessons alongside the main class teacher.\n\nThe Bridge operate a 'Bridge Pass' scheme where students in lessons feel like they need a time out or extra support can complete the rest in the Bridge.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://www.ripon.outwood.com}}\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/bsp/hi/education/03/school_tables/secondary_schools/html/815_4203.stm BBC NEWS | Education | League Tables | Ripon College]\n\n{{Schools in North Yorkshire}}\n{{Outwood Grange Academies Trust}}\n\n[[Category:Ripon]]\n[[Category:Academies in North Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 2011]]\n[[Category:2011 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Secondary schools in North Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:Outwood Grange schools|Ripon]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox school \n| name          = Outwood Academy Ripon\n| image         = \n| image_size          = \n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| logo = File:Fair use logo Outwood Academy Ripon.png \n| motto         = \"Students First\"\n| established   = <!-- {{Start date|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}} -->\n| closed        = \n| type          = [[Academy (English school)|Academy]]\n| admissions    = \n| trust         = \n| religious_affiliation      = \n| president     = \n| head_label    = Principal\n| head          = Gemma Trattles\n| chair_label   = \n| chair         = \n| founder       = \n| medium        = \n| address        = Clotherholme Road\n| location      = \n| city          = [[Ripon]]\n| district      = \n| postcode      = HG4 2DE\n| county        = [[North Yorkshire]]\n| country       = England\n| coordinates   = {{coord|54.1368|-1.5390|type:edu_region:GB_dim:100|format=dec|display=inline,title}}\n| local_authority = [[North Yorkshire County Council|North Yorkshire]]\n| dfeno         = 815/4203\n| urn           = 137412\n| ofsted        = yes\n| staff         = \n| capacity      = 782\n| enrolment    = 656 {{As of|2018|01|lc=on}}\n| gender        = [[Mixed-sex education|Mixed]]\n| lower_age     = 11\n| upper_age     = 18\n| houses        = Africa, Americas, Australasia, Europe\n| colours       = Purple and gold {{color box|#5B3393}} {{color box|#B09C78}}\n| publication   = \n| free_label_1  = \n| free_1        = \n| free_label_2  = \n| free_2        = \n| free_label_3  = \n| free_3        = \n| website       = {{URL|ripon.outwood.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Outwood Academy Ripon''' is a small [[Mixed-sex education|mixed]] [[secondary school]] and [[sixth form]] with [[Academy (English school)|academy status]] situated in the city of [[Ripon]], in [[North Yorkshire]], England.\nIt provides for children ages 11 to 18, and had an enrolment of 656 pupils in 2018.<ref name=\"gias\">{{cite web |title=Outwood Academy Ripon |url=https://get-information-schools.service.gov.uk/Establishments/Establishment/Details/137412 |website=get-information-schools.service.gov.uk |publisher=[[Department for Education]] |accessdate=7 March 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe school is operated by [[Outwood Grange Academies Trust]] and the current principal is Gemma Trattles.<ref name=\"gias\" />\n\nIt is one of over 11 secondary schools in the local area, including nearby selective [[Ripon Grammar School]], and the more distant [[Thirsk School and Sixth Form College]] and Boroughbridge High School.\n\n==History==\nThe school originally opened as a secondary modern in the 1930s. It was known as '''Ripon City School''' from the mid-1990s until 1999, when it became '''Ripon College''',  a [[Community school (England and Wales)|community school]].<ref name=\"gazette-2013\">{{cite news|title=FEATURE: Secondary education in Ripon|url=http://www.ripongazette.co.uk/news/education/feature-secondary-education-in-ripon-1-6328477|accessdate=9 June 2017|work=Ripon Gazette|publisher=Johnston Publishing|date=20 December 2013|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Ripon College|url=http://www.education.gov.uk/edubase/establishment/summary.xhtml?urn=121688|website=EduBase|publisher=[[Department for Education]]|accessdate=9 June 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 2000, teacher James Kelly was a regional winner in the \"Most Outstanding New Teacher\" category of the [[Teaching Awards]].<ref>{{cite news|title=In with a bang|url=http://education.guardian.co.uk/specialreports/teachingawards2000/story/0,,390585,00.html|accessdate=9 June 2017|work=The Guardian|publisher=Guardian News and Media|date=31 October 2000}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2011 Ripon College converted to [[Academy (English school)|academy status]]. It reopened as Outwood Academy Ripon, and became part of [[Outwood Grange Academies Trust]].<ref name=\"gazette-2013\" />\n\nOn 11 November 2015, approximately 40 pupils at the school simultaneously fell ill during an [[Armistice Day]] service. Police said students showed signs of \"sickness and feeling faint sometime between 11:00 and 11.30\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-york-north-yorkshire-34789661|title=School pupils collapse at Outwood Academy in Ripon|publisher=BBC News|date=11 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Pastoral care==\nEach pupil belongs to one of 21 [[tutor group]]s, known as vertical mentor groups (VMGs), which assemble after second lesson and take part in different activities. The mentor groups contain pupils from years 7-11 with the exception of Algeria which is purely Sixth Form.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\n==Special educational needs provision==\nA specialist team of teaching assistants and [[Special education in the United Kingdom|special educational needs]] (SEN) managers work together in 'The Hub' to ensure that students in need of extra support are getting it. Teachers from the Hub will mentor students either on site in the Hub or in the students lessons alongside the main class teacher.\n\nThe Bridge operate a 'Bridge Pass' scheme where students in lessons feel like they need a time out or extra support can complete the rest in the Bridge.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://www.ripon.outwood.com}}\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/bsp/hi/education/03/school_tables/secondary_schools/html/815_4203.stm BBC NEWS | Education | League Tables | Ripon College]\n\n{{Schools in North Yorkshire}}\n{{Outwood Grange Academies Trust}}\n\n[[Category:Ripon]]\n[[Category:Academies in North Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 2011]]\n[[Category:2011 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Secondary schools in North Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:Outwood Grange schools|Ripon]]\n", "name_user": "Keith D", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix infobox file", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Outwood_Academy_Ripon"}
{"title_page": "Unforgettable (2017 film)", "text_new": "{{short description|2017 film directed by Denise Di Novi}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Unforgettable\n| image          = Unforgettable_2017_poster.jpg\n| alt            =\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Denise Di Novi]]\n| producer      = {{Plainlist|\n* Denise Di Novi\n* Alison Greenspan\n* Ravi D. Mehta\n}}\n| writer        = [[Christina Hodson]]\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Rosario Dawson]]\n* [[Katherine Heigl]]\n* [[Geoff Stults]]\n}}<!-- Per poster and billing block -->\n| music          = [[Toby Chu]]\n| cinematography = [[Caleb Deschanel]]\n| editing        = Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Thoraval\n| studio = [[Denise Di Novi|Di Novi Pictures]]\n| distributor    = [[Warner Bros.|Warner Bros. Pictures]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2017|4|21|United States}}\n| runtime        = 100 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 99:58--><ref name=\"BOM\" />\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $26.9 million<ref name=\"cagov\">{{cite report|title=Film and Television Tax Credit Program Program 2.0|url=http://film.ca.gov/wp-content/uploads/CFC-Approved-Projects-List.pdf|publisher=[[California Film Commission]]|page=9|accessdate=October 4, 2018}}</ref>\n| gross          = $17.8 million<ref name=\"BOM\">{{cite web |title=Unforgettable (2017) |website= [[Box Office Mojo]] |url= https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=unforgettable2016.htm |accessdate=August 12, 2017}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Unforgettable''''' is a 2017 American [[drama]] [[thriller film]] directed by [[Denise Di Novi]] (in her directorial debut) and written by [[Christina Hodson]]. The film stars [[Rosario Dawson]], [[Katherine Heigl]], [[Geoff Stults]], [[Isabella Rice]], and [[Cheryl Ladd]], and follows a divorc\u00e9e who begins to torment her ex-husband's new fianc\u00e9e.\n\n[[Principal photography]] began on August 17, 2015 in [[Los Angeles]]. The film was released on April 21, 2017 by [[Warner Bros.|Warner Bros. Pictures]]. The film, which received mostly negative reviews, grossed $11.8 million in the US and $17.8 million worldwide against its $26.9 million budget.\n\n== Plot ==\nJulia Banks ([[Rosario Dawson]]) is questioned for the murder of her psychotic ex-boyfriend, Michael ([[Simon Kassianides]]). Julia claims she has been set up, despite social media conversations showing her lusting after Michael.\n\nSix months earlier, Julia receives a send-off from her boss and friend, Ali ([[Whitney Cummings]]), from her job as chief online editor for a storytelling website. Julia plans to work remotely from the mansion she will share with her fianc\u00e9 David Connover ([[Geoff Stults]]) and her soon-to-be stepdaughter Lily ([[Isabella Rice]]). At David's house, Julia is greeted by his ex-wife Tessa ([[Katherine Heigl]]), who is not coping with the end of their marriage two years earlier.\n\nThe next evening, Tessa drops something off at the house, and Lily insists she stays for dinner. Tessa criticizes Julia's cooking and leaves. Julia learns that her [[restraining order]] against Michael has expired, much to her distress.\n\nTessa is visited by \"Lovey\" ([[Cheryl Ladd]]), her controlling and belittling mother. Investigating Julia online, Tessa discovers her restraining order against Michael. She sets up a [[Facebook]] account impersonating Julia, and messages Michael, telling him how much \"Julia\" misses him.\n\nJulia receives a surprise flower delivery, sent anonymously by Tessa to make it appear Julia is having an affair. While Julia is at the door, Tessa sneaks in and steals David's watch, his grandmother's wedding ring, and a pair of Julia's panties. That afternoon, while Julia and Lily visit David at a farmer's market, Lily wanders off. Julia finds her in the arms of Tessa, who is complaining to David about Julia's incompetence as a mother. When Tessa shows up at the house, Julia confronts her for trying to reenter David's life. The women have lunch together in an attempt to reconcile, and Tessa claims that David left her was because he suspected she was having an affair. Tessa mails Michael the watch and panties.\n\nTessa tries to get Lily to ride an unruly horse at her [[equestrianism|horseback riding]] practice, but Julia notices Lily\u2019s fear and takes her home, to Tessa's annoyance. That night, Tessa pleasures herself in her car while sending [[sexting|sexually explicit messages]], posing as Julia, to Michael.\n\nTessa cuts Lily's long hair short as punishment for leaving riding practice early, leading to a heated argument with Julia. Tessa throws herself down the stairs and pretends Julia accidentally pushed her when David arrives. After taking Tessa to a hospital, David castigates Julia for treating his ex-wife so badly. Julia calls on Ali for help, and they discover Tessa\u2019s child services records; as a teenager, she attempted to kill her father when he cheated on her mother.\n\nTessa messages Michael, as Julia, saying she wants him to visit for sex. Michael enters the house when Julia is alone, and when she spurns his advances, he attacks her. A badly beaten Julia stabs him in the leg with a kitchen knife and escapes the house. Tessa, waiting outside, enters and stabs Michael in the chest.\n\nIn the present, the police release Julia, stating the investigation into Michael\u2019s death will continue. David is initially supportive after a tearful Julia explains her history with Michael, but when the police show him the \"evidence\", he becomes disillusioned and goes to Tessa's house to get Lily. There, he sees burned gloves in the fireplace and his grandmother's wedding ring on Tessa's finger, realizing that Tessa framed Julia.\n\nTessa knocks David out with a fireplace poker. Julia arrives and tries to call 9-1-1, but is attacked by Tessa. Subduing Tessa, Julia rushes to revive David, but Tessa attacks her with a knife. Seeing herself in a mirror, Tessa realizes the monster she has become and stabs herself in the stomach. Dying, Tessa begs Julia to not let Lily remember her like this.\n\nSix months later, David and Julia are married and have moved into a new house with Lily. Julia answers the door to find Lovey wanting to see her granddaughter. Julia looks on in horror as Lovey hugs Lily.\n\n== Cast ==\n<!--- all opening credit names/order, with roles per closing credits --->\n* [[Rosario Dawson]] as Julia Banks, David's fianc\u00e9e\n* [[Katherine Heigl]] as Tessa Connover, David's ex-wife\n* [[Geoff Stults]] as David Connover, Tessa's ex-husband and Lily's father\n* [[Cheryl Ladd]] as Helen/\"Lovey\", Tessa's mother\n* [[Sarah Burns]] as Sarah, David's friend since childhood\n* [[Whitney Cummings]] as Ali, Julia\u2019s best friend\n* [[Simon Kassianides]] as Michael Vargas, Julia's abusive and violent ex-boyfriend\n* [[Isabella Rice|Isabella Kai Rice]] as Lily Connover, Tessa and David's daughter\n* [[Robert Wisdom|Robert Ray Wisdom]] as Detective Pope\n* [[Jayson Blair (actor)|Jayson Blair]] as Jason\n\n== Production ==\nOn January 9, 2014, it was announced that [[Warner Bros.]] had hired [[Amma Asante]] to direct the [[female]]-centric thriller ''Unforgettable''. [[Denise Di Novi]] was set to produce the film along with [[Alison Greenspan]], while [[Christina Hodson]] was writing the script.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/news/warner-bros-rings-belle-director-for-new-thriller-exclusive-1201041518/|title=Warner Bros. Rings \u2018Belle\u2019 Director for New Thriller (EXCLUSIVE)|date=January 9, 2014|work=variety.com|last2=Kroll|first2=Justin|last1=McNary|first1=Dave|accessdate=August 22, 2015}}</ref> On December 2, 2014, [[Kate Hudson]] and [[Kerry Washington]] were cast as the leads in the film, about a man who is threatened by his ex-wife.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://deadline.com/2014/12/kate-hudson-and-kerry-washington-prove-unforgettable-for-amma-asante-1201306216/|title=Kate Hudson & Kerry Washington Prove \u2018Unforgettable\u2019 For Amma Asante|date=December 2, 2014|work=deadline.com|last1=Jaafar|first1=Ali|accessdate=August 22, 2015}}</ref> On June 22, 2015, after director Asante and actresses Hudson and Washington had left the project, it was revealed that producer Di Novi would make her directorial debut with the film.<ref name=June2015THR>{{cite news|last1=Kit|first1=Borys|title=Producer Denise Di Novi to Make Directorial Debut With Warner Bros. Thriller (Exclusive)|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/producer-denise-di-novi-make-800376|accessdate=August 22, 2015 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=June 22, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Sneider|first1=Jeff|title=Kerry Washington, Kate Hudson Exit Warner Bros. Thriller 'Unforgettable' |url=https://www.thewrap.com/kerry-washington-kate-hudson-exit-warner-bros-thriller-unforgettable/|accessdate=August 22, 2015|work=thewrap.com|date=June 22, 2015}}</ref> It was also revealed that [[David Leslie Johnson]] had co-written the script along with Hodson.<ref name=\"June2015THR\" /> On August 12, 2015, [[Katherine Heigl]] was cast to play Tessa Connover, the sly and mentally unstable divorced mother who threatens her ex-husband, daughter, and her ex-husband's new girlfriend.<ref name=\"Aug2015CS\" /><ref name=\"HeiglCast\">{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/katherine-heigl-unforgettable-exclusive-1201568554/|title=Katherine Heigl to Star in Warner Bros. Thriller \u2018Unforgettable\u2019 (EXCLUSIVE)|date=August 12, 2015|work=variety.com|last1=Kroll|first1=Justin|accessdate=August 22, 2015}}</ref> The same day, [[Rosario Dawson]] was cast as the girlfriend, Julia Banks, who tries to fight back against Tessa.<ref name=\"Aug2015CS\" /><ref name=DawsonCast>{{cite news|last1=Kit|first1=Borys|title=Rosario Dawson Joining Katherine Heigl in 'Unforgettable' Thriller (Exclusive)|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/rosario-dawson-joining-katherine-heigl-814830|accessdate=August 22, 2015|work=hollywoodreporter.com|date=August 12, 2015}}</ref> On August 21, 2015, more cast was announced, including [[Geoff Stults]] as David, the ex-husband, [[Isabella Rice]] as Lily, the daughter, [[Cheryl Ladd]] as Heigl's character's mother, and [[Simon Kassianides]], [[Whitney Cummings]], and [[Robert Wisdom]].<ref name=\"Aug2015CS\" /><ref name=\"Aug2015Deadline\">{{cite news|url=https://deadline.com/2015/08/ella-anderson-mothers-day-clementine-nicholson-underworld-next-generation-1201500643/|title=Ella Anderson Joins \u2018Mother\u2019s Day\u2019 Cast; Cheryl Ladd Is \u2018Unforgettable\u2019|date=August 21, 2015|work=deadline.com|last1=Pedersen|first1=Erik|accessdate=August 22, 2015}}</ref>\n\nRavi D. Mehta and Emanuel Michael were also announced as producers of the film, along with other members of the creative team, including cinematographer [[Caleb Deschanel]], production designer [[Nelson Coates]], editor Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Thoraval, and costume designer Marian Toy.<ref name=\"Aug2015CS\" />\n\n=== Filming ===\n[[Principal photography]] on the film began on August 17, 2015, in and around [[Los Angeles]].<ref name=Aug2015CS>{{cite news|last1=Evry|first1=Max|title=Unforgettable Begins Production with Katherine Heigl and Rosario Dawson|url=https://www.comingsoon.net/movies/news/474787-unforgettable-begins-production-with-katherine-heigl-and-rosario-dawson|accessdate=August 22, 2015|work=comingsoon.net|date=August 21, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"DawsonCast\" />\n\n== Release ==\n''Unforgettable'' was released on April 21, 2017, by [[Warner Bros. Pictures]].\n\n===Box office===\n''Unforgettable'' grossed $11.4 million in the United States and Canada and $6.4 million in other territories for a worldwide gross of $17.8 million.<ref name=\"BOM\" /> There were different estimates of the budget, the [[Los Angeles Times]] estimated the film had a production budget of $12 million,<ref name=\"latimes-budget\">{{cite web |title='Fate' to top box office as Hollywood awaits 'Guardians of the Galaxy |website= [[Los Angeles Times]] |url= https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/la-fi-ct-movie-projector-fate-furious-20170418-htmlstory.html |accessdate=April 19, 2017}}</ref> California government reports state that the film spent $26.9 million on location that was eligible for tax rebates.<ref name=\"cagov\" />\n\nIn the United States and Canada, ''Unforgettable'' opened alongside ''[[The Promise (2016 American film)|The Promise]]'', ''[[Born in China]]'', ''[[Free Fire]]'' and ''[[Phoenix Forgotten]]'', and was initially projected to gross around $7 million from 2,417 theaters in its opening weekend.<ref name=\"preview\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/box-office-fate-of-the-furious-unforgettable-1202347619/|title=Box Office: \u2018Unforgettable\u2019 to Get Burned by \u2018Fate of the Furious\u2019|date=April 19, 2017|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]}}</ref> However, after grossing just $1.7 million on Friday, weekend projections were lowered to $4\u20135 million. It ended up opening to $4.8 million, finishing 7th at the box office.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/04/the-promise-free-fire-born-in-china-unforgettable-phoenix-forgotten-previews-box-office-1202073216/|title=\u2018Fate Of The Furious\u2019 Drives Five Wide Releases Off The Road With $38.6M Second Weekend|date=April 23, 2017|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\nOn [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film has an approval rating of 26% based on 117 reviews, with an average rating of 3.96/10. The site's critical consensus reads, \"''Unforgettable''{{'}}s talented cast makes this domestic thriller consistently watchable, even if its failure to fully embrace its premise's campy possibilities prevents it from living up to its title.\"<ref>{{cite web |title= Unforgettable (2017) |website= [[Rotten Tomatoes]] |url= https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/unforgettable_2017 |accessdate=January 8, 2020}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a score of 45 out of 100, based on 27 critics, indicating \"mixed or average reviews\".<ref>{{cite web | title=Unforgettable reviews | work=[[Metacritic]] | publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] | url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/unforgettable | accessdate=May 4, 2017 }}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"C\" on an A+ to F scale.<ref name=\"CinemaScore\">{{cite web |url= https://www.cinemascore.com/publicsearch/index/title/ |title= Cinemascore |work= [[CinemaScore]] |url-status= dead |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181220122629/https://www.cinemascore.com/publicsearch/index/title/ |archive-date= 2018-12-20 }}</ref>\n\nVince Mancini of ''[[Uproxx]]'' called the film \"a surprisingly well-executed version of exactly what you assumed it would be. Which is to say, it\u2019s a 'psycho ex' movie that\u2019s fun, but doesn\u2019t exactly reinvent the genre...It\u2019s fun while it lasts, let\u2019s say (the opposite of its title, basically). Sometimes that\u2019s enough, but your mileage may vary.\"<ref>{{cite web |title= \u2018Unforgettable\u2019 Is An Enjoyable Genre Exercise Starring Katherine Heigl As A Psycho Ex |last= Mancini |first= Vince |date= April 20, 2017 |url=http://uproxx.com/filmdrunk/unforgettable-movie-review/ |website=Uproxx }}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website}}\n* {{IMDb title|3462710}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|unforgettable_2017}}\n\n[[Category:2017 films]]\n[[Category:2010s thriller drama films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American thriller drama films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about interracial romance]]\n[[Category:Films about stalking]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Denise Di Novi]]\n[[Category:Films set in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Warner Bros. films]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Christina Hodson]]\n[[Category:American romantic thriller films]]\n[[Category:2017 directorial debut films]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2017 film directed by Denise Di Novi}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Unforgettable\n| image          = Unforgettable_2017_poster.jpg\n| alt            =\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Denise Di Novi]]\n| producer      = {{Plainlist|\n* Denise Di Novi\n* Alison Greenspan\n* Ravi D. Mehta\n}}\n| writer        = [[Christina Hodson]]\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Rosario Dawson]]\n* [[Katherine Heigl]]\n* [[Geoff Stults]]\n}}<!-- Per poster and billing block -->\n| music          = [[Toby Chu]]\n| cinematography = [[Caleb Deschanel]]\n| editing        = Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Thoraval\n| studio = [[Denise Di Novi|Di Novi Pictures]]\n| distributor    = [[Warner Bros.|Warner Bros. Pictures]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2017|4|21|United States}}\n| runtime        = 100 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 99:58--><ref name=\"BOM\" />\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $26.9 million<ref name=\"cagov\">{{cite report|title=Film and Television Tax Credit Program Program 2.0|url=http://film.ca.gov/wp-content/uploads/CFC-Approved-Projects-List.pdf|publisher=[[California Film Commission]]|page=9|accessdate=October 4, 2018}}</ref>\n| gross          = $17.8 million<ref name=\"BOM\">{{cite web |title=Unforgettable (2017) |website= [[Box Office Mojo]] |url= https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=unforgettable2016.htm |accessdate=August 12, 2017}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Unforgettable''''' is a 2017 American [[drama]] [[thriller film]] directed by [[Denise Di Novi]] (in her directorial debut) and written by [[Christina Hodson]]. The film stars [[Rosario Dawson]], [[Katherine Heigl]], [[Geoff Stults]], [[Isabella Rice]], and [[Cheryl Ladd]], and follows a divorc\u00e9e who begins to torment her ex-husband's new fianc\u00e9e.\n\n[[Principal photography]] began on August 17, 2015 in [[Los Angeles]]. The film was released on April 21, 2017 by [[Warner Bros.|Warner Bros. Pictures]]. The film, which received mostly negative reviews, grossed $11.8 million in the US and $17.8 million worldwide against its $12 million budget.\n\n== Plot ==\nJulia Banks ([[Rosario Dawson]]) is questioned for the murder of her psychotic ex-boyfriend, Michael ([[Simon Kassianides]]). Julia claims she has been set up, despite social media conversations showing her lusting after Michael.\n\nSix months earlier, Julia receives a send-off from her boss and friend, Ali ([[Whitney Cummings]]), from her job as chief online editor for a storytelling website. Julia plans to work remotely from the mansion she will share with her fianc\u00e9 David Connover ([[Geoff Stults]]) and her soon-to-be stepdaughter Lily ([[Isabella Rice]]). At David's house, Julia is greeted by his ex-wife Tessa ([[Katherine Heigl]]), who is not coping with the end of their marriage two years earlier.\n\nThe next evening, Tessa drops something off at the house, and Lily insists she stays for dinner. Tessa criticizes Julia's cooking and leaves. Julia learns that her [[restraining order]] against Michael has expired, much to her distress.\n\nTessa is visited by \"Lovey\" ([[Cheryl Ladd]]), her controlling and belittling mother. Investigating Julia online, Tessa discovers her restraining order against Michael. She sets up a [[Facebook]] account impersonating Julia, and messages Michael, telling him how much \"Julia\" misses him.\n\nJulia receives a surprise flower delivery, sent anonymously by Tessa to make it appear Julia is having an affair. While Julia is at the door, Tessa sneaks in and steals David's watch, his grandmother's wedding ring, and a pair of Julia's panties. That afternoon, while Julia and Lily visit David at a farmer's market, Lily wanders off. Julia finds her in the arms of Tessa, who is complaining to David about Julia's incompetence as a mother. When Tessa shows up at the house, Julia confronts her for trying to reenter David's life. The women have lunch together in an attempt to reconcile, and Tessa claims that David left her was because he suspected she was having an affair. Tessa mails Michael the watch and panties.\n\nTessa tries to get Lily to ride an unruly horse at her [[equestrianism|horseback riding]] practice, but Julia notices Lily\u2019s fear and takes her home, to Tessa's annoyance. That night, Tessa pleasures herself in her car while sending [[sexting|sexually explicit messages]], posing as Julia, to Michael.\n\nTessa cuts Lily's long hair short as punishment for leaving riding practice early, leading to a heated argument with Julia. Tessa throws herself down the stairs and pretends Julia accidentally pushed her when David arrives. After taking Tessa to a hospital, David castigates Julia for treating his ex-wife so badly. Julia calls on Ali for help, and they discover Tessa\u2019s child services records; as a teenager, she attempted to kill her father when he cheated on her mother.\n\nTessa messages Michael, as Julia, saying she wants him to visit for sex. Michael enters the house when Julia is alone, and when she spurns his advances, he attacks her. A badly beaten Julia stabs him in the leg with a kitchen knife and escapes the house. Tessa, waiting outside, enters and stabs Michael in the chest.\n\nIn the present, the police release Julia, stating the investigation into Michael\u2019s death will continue. David is initially supportive after a tearful Julia explains her history with Michael, but when the police show him the \"evidence\", he becomes disillusioned and goes to Tessa's house to get Lily. There, he sees burned gloves in the fireplace and his grandmother's wedding ring on Tessa's finger, realizing that Tessa framed Julia.\n\nTessa knocks David out with a fireplace poker. Julia arrives and tries to call 9-1-1, but is attacked by Tessa. Subduing Tessa, Julia rushes to revive David, but Tessa attacks her with a knife. Seeing herself in a mirror, Tessa realizes the monster she has become and stabs herself in the stomach. Dying, Tessa begs Julia to not let Lily remember her like this.\n\nSix months later, David and Julia are married and have moved into a new house with Lily. Julia answers the door to find Lovey wanting to see her granddaughter. Julia looks on in horror as Lovey hugs Lily.\n\n== Cast ==\n<!--- all opening credit names/order, with roles per closing credits --->\n* [[Rosario Dawson]] as Julia Banks, David's fianc\u00e9e\n* [[Katherine Heigl]] as Tessa Connover, David's ex-wife\n* [[Geoff Stults]] as David Connover, Tessa's ex-husband and Lily's father\n* [[Cheryl Ladd]] as Helen/\"Lovey\", Tessa's mother\n* [[Sarah Burns]] as Sarah, David's friend since childhood\n* [[Whitney Cummings]] as Ali, Julia\u2019s best friend\n* [[Simon Kassianides]] as Michael Vargas, Julia's abusive and violent ex-boyfriend\n* [[Isabella Rice|Isabella Kai Rice]] as Lily Connover, Tessa and David's daughter\n* [[Robert Wisdom|Robert Ray Wisdom]] as Detective Pope\n* [[Jayson Blair (actor)|Jayson Blair]] as Jason\n\n== Production ==\nOn January 9, 2014, it was announced that [[Warner Bros.]] had hired [[Amma Asante]] to direct the [[female]]-centric thriller ''Unforgettable''. [[Denise Di Novi]] was set to produce the film along with [[Alison Greenspan]], while [[Christina Hodson]] was writing the script.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/news/warner-bros-rings-belle-director-for-new-thriller-exclusive-1201041518/|title=Warner Bros. Rings \u2018Belle\u2019 Director for New Thriller (EXCLUSIVE)|date=January 9, 2014|work=variety.com|last2=Kroll|first2=Justin|last1=McNary|first1=Dave|accessdate=August 22, 2015}}</ref> On December 2, 2014, [[Kate Hudson]] and [[Kerry Washington]] were cast as the leads in the film, about a man who is threatened by his ex-wife.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://deadline.com/2014/12/kate-hudson-and-kerry-washington-prove-unforgettable-for-amma-asante-1201306216/|title=Kate Hudson & Kerry Washington Prove \u2018Unforgettable\u2019 For Amma Asante|date=December 2, 2014|work=deadline.com|last1=Jaafar|first1=Ali|accessdate=August 22, 2015}}</ref> On June 22, 2015, after director Asante and actresses Hudson and Washington had left the project, it was revealed that producer Di Novi would make her directorial debut with the film.<ref name=June2015THR>{{cite news|last1=Kit|first1=Borys|title=Producer Denise Di Novi to Make Directorial Debut With Warner Bros. Thriller (Exclusive)|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/producer-denise-di-novi-make-800376|accessdate=August 22, 2015 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=June 22, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Sneider|first1=Jeff|title=Kerry Washington, Kate Hudson Exit Warner Bros. Thriller 'Unforgettable' |url=https://www.thewrap.com/kerry-washington-kate-hudson-exit-warner-bros-thriller-unforgettable/|accessdate=August 22, 2015|work=thewrap.com|date=June 22, 2015}}</ref> It was also revealed that [[David Leslie Johnson]] had co-written the script along with Hodson.<ref name=\"June2015THR\" /> On August 12, 2015, [[Katherine Heigl]] was cast to play Tessa Connover, the sly and mentally unstable divorced mother who threatens her ex-husband, daughter, and her ex-husband's new girlfriend.<ref name=\"Aug2015CS\" /><ref name=\"HeiglCast\">{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/katherine-heigl-unforgettable-exclusive-1201568554/|title=Katherine Heigl to Star in Warner Bros. Thriller \u2018Unforgettable\u2019 (EXCLUSIVE)|date=August 12, 2015|work=variety.com|last1=Kroll|first1=Justin|accessdate=August 22, 2015}}</ref> The same day, [[Rosario Dawson]] was cast as the girlfriend, Julia Banks, who tries to fight back against Tessa.<ref name=\"Aug2015CS\" /><ref name=DawsonCast>{{cite news|last1=Kit|first1=Borys|title=Rosario Dawson Joining Katherine Heigl in 'Unforgettable' Thriller (Exclusive)|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/rosario-dawson-joining-katherine-heigl-814830|accessdate=August 22, 2015|work=hollywoodreporter.com|date=August 12, 2015}}</ref> On August 21, 2015, more cast was announced, including [[Geoff Stults]] as David, the ex-husband, [[Isabella Rice]] as Lily, the daughter, [[Cheryl Ladd]] as Heigl's character's mother, and [[Simon Kassianides]], [[Whitney Cummings]], and [[Robert Wisdom]].<ref name=\"Aug2015CS\" /><ref name=\"Aug2015Deadline\">{{cite news|url=https://deadline.com/2015/08/ella-anderson-mothers-day-clementine-nicholson-underworld-next-generation-1201500643/|title=Ella Anderson Joins \u2018Mother\u2019s Day\u2019 Cast; Cheryl Ladd Is \u2018Unforgettable\u2019|date=August 21, 2015|work=deadline.com|last1=Pedersen|first1=Erik|accessdate=August 22, 2015}}</ref>\n\nRavi D. Mehta and Emanuel Michael were also announced as producers of the film, along with other members of the creative team, including cinematographer [[Caleb Deschanel]], production designer [[Nelson Coates]], editor Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Thoraval, and costume designer Marian Toy.<ref name=\"Aug2015CS\" />\n\n=== Filming ===\n[[Principal photography]] on the film began on August 17, 2015, in and around [[Los Angeles]].<ref name=Aug2015CS>{{cite news|last1=Evry|first1=Max|title=Unforgettable Begins Production with Katherine Heigl and Rosario Dawson|url=https://www.comingsoon.net/movies/news/474787-unforgettable-begins-production-with-katherine-heigl-and-rosario-dawson|accessdate=August 22, 2015|work=comingsoon.net|date=August 21, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"DawsonCast\" />\n\n== Release ==\n''Unforgettable'' was released on April 21, 2017, by [[Warner Bros. Pictures]].\n\n===Box office===\n''Unforgettable'' grossed $11.4 million in the United States and Canada and $6.4 million in other territories for a worldwide gross of $17.8 million.<ref name=\"BOM\" /> There were different estimates of the budget, the [[Los Angeles Times]] estimated the film had a production budget of $12 million,<ref name=\"latimes-budget\">{{cite web |title='Fate' to top box office as Hollywood awaits 'Guardians of the Galaxy |website= [[Los Angeles Times]] |url= https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/la-fi-ct-movie-projector-fate-furious-20170418-htmlstory.html |accessdate=April 19, 2017}}</ref> California government reports state that the film spent $26.9 million on location that was eligible for tax rebates.<ref name=\"cagov\" />\n\nIn the United States and Canada, ''Unforgettable'' opened alongside ''[[The Promise (2016 American film)|The Promise]]'', ''[[Born in China]]'', ''[[Free Fire]]'' and ''[[Phoenix Forgotten]]'', and was initially projected to gross around $7 million from 2,417 theaters in its opening weekend.<ref name=\"preview\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/box-office-fate-of-the-furious-unforgettable-1202347619/|title=Box Office: \u2018Unforgettable\u2019 to Get Burned by \u2018Fate of the Furious\u2019|date=April 19, 2017|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]}}</ref> However, after grossing just $1.7 million on Friday, weekend projections were lowered to $4\u20135 million. It ended up opening to $4.8 million, finishing 7th at the box office.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/04/the-promise-free-fire-born-in-china-unforgettable-phoenix-forgotten-previews-box-office-1202073216/|title=\u2018Fate Of The Furious\u2019 Drives Five Wide Releases Off The Road With $38.6M Second Weekend|date=April 23, 2017|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\nOn [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film has an approval rating of 26% based on 117 reviews, with an average rating of 3.96/10. The site's critical consensus reads, \"''Unforgettable''{{'}}s talented cast makes this domestic thriller consistently watchable, even if its failure to fully embrace its premise's campy possibilities prevents it from living up to its title.\"<ref>{{cite web |title= Unforgettable (2017) |website= [[Rotten Tomatoes]] |url= https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/unforgettable_2017 |accessdate=January 8, 2020}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a score of 45 out of 100, based on 27 critics, indicating \"mixed or average reviews\".<ref>{{cite web | title=Unforgettable reviews | work=[[Metacritic]] | publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] | url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/unforgettable | accessdate=May 4, 2017 }}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"C\" on an A+ to F scale.<ref name=\"CinemaScore\">{{cite web |url= https://www.cinemascore.com/publicsearch/index/title/ |title= Cinemascore |work= [[CinemaScore]] |url-status= dead |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181220122629/https://www.cinemascore.com/publicsearch/index/title/ |archive-date= 2018-12-20 }}</ref>\n\nVince Mancini of ''[[Uproxx]]'' called the film \"a surprisingly well-executed version of exactly what you assumed it would be. Which is to say, it\u2019s a 'psycho ex' movie that\u2019s fun, but doesn\u2019t exactly reinvent the genre...It\u2019s fun while it lasts, let\u2019s say (the opposite of its title, basically). Sometimes that\u2019s enough, but your mileage may vary.\"<ref>{{cite web |title= \u2018Unforgettable\u2019 Is An Enjoyable Genre Exercise Starring Katherine Heigl As A Psycho Ex |last= Mancini |first= Vince |date= April 20, 2017 |url=http://uproxx.com/filmdrunk/unforgettable-movie-review/ |website=Uproxx }}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website}}\n* {{IMDb title|3462710}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|unforgettable_2017}}\n\n[[Category:2017 films]]\n[[Category:2010s thriller drama films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American thriller drama films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about interracial romance]]\n[[Category:Films about stalking]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Denise Di Novi]]\n[[Category:Films set in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Warner Bros. films]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Christina Hodson]]\n[[Category:American romantic thriller films]]\n[[Category:2017 directorial debut films]]\n", "name_user": "Davefelmer", "label": "safe", "comment": "corrected figures", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unforgettable_(2017_film)"}
{"title_page": "French ship Brillant (1774)", "text_new": "{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=Image:Protecteur mg 9407.jpg\n|Ship caption=Model of a 64-gun ship from the 1770s of the same type as the ''Brillant''\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship country=France\n|Ship flag=[[File:Flag of the Kingdom of France (1814-1830).svg|45px|French Royal Navy Ensign]]\n|Ship name=''Brillant''\n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship builder=Brest<ref name=\"roche86\" />\n|Ship laid down=November 1772<ref name=\"roche86\" />\n|Ship launched=September 1774<ref name=\"roche86\" />\n|Ship acquired=\n|Ship commissioned=December 1774<ref name=\"roche86\" />\n|Ship decommissioned=\n|Ship in service=\n|Ship out of service=June 1786<ref name=\"roche86\" />\n|Ship renamed=\n|Ship struck=\n|Ship reinstated=\n|Ship honours=\n|Ship captured=\n|Ship fate=\n|Ship status=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=<ref name=\"Lavery-SoLvol1\">Lavery, Ships of the Line vol.1. p182.</ref>\n|Ship class=[[Solitaire class ship of the line|''Solitaire'' class ship of the line]]\n|Ship tons burthen=1521 [[Long ton|tons]] (1545.4 [[tonne]]s)\n|Ship length=51 metres <ref name=\"roche86\">Roche, vol.1, p.86</ref>\n|Ship beam=13.2 metres <ref name=\"roche86\" />\n|Ship draught=6.4 metres <ref name=\"roche86\" />\n|Ship hold depth=\n|Ship sail plan=[[Full rigged ship]]\n|Ship propulsion=Sails\n|Ship complement=\n|Ship armament=*26\u00d7[[24-pounder long gun]]s\n*28\u00d7[[12-pounder long gun]]s\n*10\u00d7[[6-pounder long gun]]s <ref name=\"roche86\" />\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n\n'''''Brillant''''' was a 64-gun [[Solitaire class ship of the line|''Solitaire''-class]] [[ship of the line]] of the [[French Navy]].\n\n== Career ==\n''Brillant'' served in [[Pierre Andr\u00e9 de Suffren|Suffren]]'s campaign in the Indian Ocean, taking part in the [[Battle of Cuddalore (1783)|Battle of Cuddalore]]. She was the main unit of the French force that drove away Commodore [[Edward Vernon|Vernon]]'s squadron at the [[Siege of Pondicherry (1778)|Siege of Pondicherry]] on 10 August 1779, and distinguished herself at the [[Battle of Sadras]].<ref name=\"roche86\" /> She was present at the battles of [[Battle of Negapatam (1782)|Negapatam]] under Captain [[Armand de Saint-F\u00e9lix]].<ref name=cunat169>Cunat, p.169</ref>\n\nIn July 1782, in the wake of the [[Battle of Negapatam (1782)|Battle of Negapatam]], Suffren transfered Saint-F\u00e9lix to [[French ship Art\u00e9sien|''Art\u00e9sien'']]{{refn|The captain of ''Art\u00e9sien'', Bid\u00e9 de Maureville, had fallen out of favour with Suffren following the Battle of Negapatam<ref name=cunat180 />|group=Note}} and replaced him with Beaulieu.{{refn|Beaulieu being himself replaced by Chevalier de Pierre-Vert at the command of [[French frigate Bellone (1778)|''Bellone'']].<ref name=cunat180>Cunat, p.180</ref>\n<ref name=cunat180 />|group=Note}} The frigate [[French frigate Pourvoyeuse (1772)|''Pourvoyeuse'']] had to give her mainmast to replace that of ''Brillant'', receiving herself that of [[Fortitude (1780 EIC ship)|''Fortitude'']].<ref>Troude, p. 188</ref> \n\nBrillant fought at the [[Battle of Trincomalee|Trincomalee]]<ref name=\"roche86\" /> between 25 August and 3 September 1782 under Lieutenant de Kersauson, as well as in the [[Battle of Cuddalore (1783)|Battle of Cuddalore]] on 20 June 1783.\n\n== Fate ==\nAfter returning to France, ''Brillant'' was hulked in Cherbourg from 1787. She was struck in 1795, and broken up in 1797. <ref name=\"roche86\" />\n\n==Notes, citations, and references==\n\n===Notes===\n{{Reflist|group=Note}}\n\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n===References===\n*{{cite book|title=Histoire maritime de France|last=Gu\u00e9rin|first=L\u00e9on|authorlink=L\u00e9on Gu\u00e9rin|year=1857|publisher=Dufour et Mulat|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=95BKAAAAMAAJ|language=French|volume=5}}\n*Lavery, Brian (2003) ''The Ship of the Line - Volume 1: The development of the battlefleet 1650-1850.'' Conway Maritime Press. {{ISBN|0-85177-252-8}}.\n*{{Cite book|first=Jean-Michel |last=Roche |year=2005 |chapter= |title=Dictionnaire des b\u00e2timents de la flotte de guerre fran\u00e7aise de Colbert \u00e0 nos jours 1 1671 - 1870 |isbn=978-2-9525917-0-6 |oclc=165892922 |page=48}}\n*{{Cite book|first=On\u00e9sime-Joachim|last=Troude|authorlink=On\u00e9sime-Joachim Troude|year=1867|publisher=Challamel ain\u00e9|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TwZv6FX-RpsC|title=Batailles navales de la France|language=French|volume=2}}\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brillant (1774)}}\n[[Category:Ships of the line of the French Navy]]\n[[Category:1774 ships]]\n[[Category:Solitaire-class ships of the line]]\n", "text_old": "{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=Image:Protecteur mg 9407.jpg\n|Ship caption=Model of a 64-gun ship from the 1770s of the same type as the ''Brillant''\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship country=France\n|Ship flag=[[File:Flag of the Kingdom of France (1814-1830).svg|45px|French Royal Navy Ensign]]\n|Ship name=''Brillant''\n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship builder=Brest<ref name=\"roche86\" />\n|Ship laid down=November 1772<ref name=\"roche86\" />\n|Ship launched=September 1774<ref name=\"roche86\" />\n|Ship acquired=\n|Ship commissioned=December 1774<ref name=\"roche86\" />\n|Ship decommissioned=\n|Ship in service=\n|Ship out of service=June 1786<ref name=\"roche86\" />\n|Ship renamed=\n|Ship struck=\n|Ship reinstated=\n|Ship honours=\n|Ship captured=\n|Ship fate=\n|Ship status=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=<ref name=\"Lavery-SoLvol1\">Lavery, Ships of the Line vol.1. p182.</ref>\n|Ship class=[[Solitaire class ship of the line|''Solitaire'' class ship of the line]]\n|Ship tons burthen=1521 [[Long ton|tons]] (1545.4 [[tonne]]s)\n|Ship length=51 metres <ref name=\"roche86\">Roche, vol.1, p.86</ref>\n|Ship beam=13.2 metres <ref name=\"roche86\" />\n|Ship draught=6.4 metres <ref name=\"roche86\" />\n|Ship hold depth=\n|Ship sail plan=[[Full rigged ship]]\n|Ship propulsion=Sails\n|Ship complement=\n|Ship armament=*26\u00d7[[24-pounder long gun]]s\n*28\u00d7[[12-pounder long gun]]s\n*10\u00d7[[6-pounder long gun]]s <ref name=\"roche86\" />\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n\n'''''Brillant''''' was a 64-gun [[Solitaire class ship of the line|''Solitaire''-class]] [[ship of the line]] of the [[French Navy]].\n\n== Career ==\n''Brillant'' served in [[Pierre Andr\u00e9 de Suffren|Suffren]]'s campaign in the Indian Ocean, taking part in the [[Battle of Cuddalore (1783)|Battle of Cuddalore]]. She was the main unit of the French force that drove away Commodore [[Edward Vernon|Vernon]]'s squadron at the [[Siege of Pondicherry (1778)|Siege of Pondicherry]] on 10 August 1779, and distinguished herself at the [[Battle of Sadras]].<ref name=\"roche86\" /> She was present at the battles of [[Battle of Negapatam (1782)|Negapatam]] under Captain [[Armand de Saint-F\u00e9lix]].<ref name=cunat169>Cunat, p.169</ref>\n\nIn July 1782, in the wake of the [[Battle of Negapatam (1782)|Battle of Negapatam]], Suffren transfered Saint-F\u00e9lix to [[French ship Art\u00e9sien|''Art\u00e9sien'']]{{refn|The captain of ''Art\u00e9sien'', Bid\u00e9 de Maureville, had fallen out of favour with Suffren following the Battle of Negapatam<ref name=cunat180 />|group=Note}} and replaced him with Beaulieu.{{refn|Beaulieu being himself replace by Chevalier de Pierre-Vert at the command of [[French frigate Bellone (1778)|''Bellone'']].<ref name=cunat180>Cunat, p.180</ref>\n<ref name=cunat180 />|group=Note}} The frigate [[French frigate Pourvoyeuse (1772)|''Pourvoyeuse'']] had to give her mainmast to replace that of ''Brillant'', receiving herself that of [[Fortitude (1780 EIC ship)|''Fortitude'']].<ref>Troude, p. 188</ref> \n\nBrillant fought at the [[Battle of Trincomalee|Trincomalee]]<ref name=\"roche86\" /> between 25 August and 3 September 1782 under Lieutenant de Kersauson, as well as in the [[Battle of Cuddalore (1783)|Battle of Cuddalore]] on 20 June 1783.\n\n== Fate ==\nAfter returning to France, ''Brillant'' was hulked in Cherbourg from 1787. She was struck in 1795, and broken up in 1797. <ref name=\"roche86\" />\n\n==Notes, citations, and references==\n\n===Notes===\n{{Reflist|group=Note}}\n\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n===References===\n*{{cite book|title=Histoire maritime de France|last=Gu\u00e9rin|first=L\u00e9on|authorlink=L\u00e9on Gu\u00e9rin|year=1857|publisher=Dufour et Mulat|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=95BKAAAAMAAJ|language=French|volume=5}}\n*Lavery, Brian (2003) ''The Ship of the Line - Volume 1: The development of the battlefleet 1650-1850.'' Conway Maritime Press. {{ISBN|0-85177-252-8}}.\n*{{Cite book|first=Jean-Michel |last=Roche |year=2005 |chapter= |title=Dictionnaire des b\u00e2timents de la flotte de guerre fran\u00e7aise de Colbert \u00e0 nos jours 1 1671 - 1870 |isbn=978-2-9525917-0-6 |oclc=165892922 |page=48}}\n*{{Cite book|first=On\u00e9sime-Joachim|last=Troude|authorlink=On\u00e9sime-Joachim Troude|year=1867|publisher=Challamel ain\u00e9|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TwZv6FX-RpsC|title=Batailles navales de la France|language=French|volume=2}}\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brillant (1774)}}\n[[Category:Ships of the line of the French Navy]]\n[[Category:1774 ships]]\n[[Category:Solitaire-class ships of the line]]\n", "name_user": "Rama", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/French_ship_Brillant_(1774)"}
{"title_page": "Rebecca D. Jackson", "text_new": "{{short description|Professor of endocrinology, diabetes and metabolism at Ohio State University}}\n'''Rebecca D. Jackson''' (born 1955) Is a medical researcher, medical practitioner and professor of [[endocrinology]], [[diabetes]] and [[metabolism]]. Her research has been significant in the understanding and treatment of osteoporosis.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web |title=biography - Rebecca Jackson, MD (Ohio) |url=https://wayback.archive-it.org/org-350/20190508153453/https://www.nlm.nih.gov/exhibition/locallegends/Biographies/Jackson_Rebecca.html |website=wayback.archive-it.org}}</ref>\n\nJackson is director of the Center for Women's Health, the founding director of the [[Ohio State University]] Center for Clinical and Translational Science, associate dean for Clinical and Translational Research, and professor of Endocrinology, Diabetes, and Metabolism at the Ohio State University.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web |title=Rebecca D. Jackson, M.D. |url=https://prevention.nih.gov/research-priorities/research-needs-and-gaps/pathways-prevention/appropriate-use-drug-therapies-osteoporotic-fracture-prevention/workshop-agenda/rebecca-d-jackson-md |website=Office of Disease Prevention |language=en}}</ref> In 2008, she was elected as a Fellow of the [[American Association for the Advancement of Science]] and received the OSU Distinguished Scholar Award, one of Ohio University's highest research honours, in 2015.\n\n== Education ==\nJackson received her medical degree from Ohio State University College of Medicine in 1978.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite web|url=https://wexnermedical.osu.edu/find-a-doctor/rebecca-jackson-md-1315|title=Rebecca Jackson|website=wexnermedical.osu.edu}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nJackson was involved in one of the first studies to show that weight lifting rather than walking was more beneficial to maintaining bone density: that the ideal exercise to stimulate bone formation is force rather than repetition. She and her colleagues have also been involved in one of the landmark studies examining bisphosphonates, a new class of medications for treating postmenopausal osteoporosis.<ref name=\"auto\"/> She has co-authored hundreds of articles that have appeared in such well-respected publications as American Journal of Preventive Medicine, Arthritis & Rheumatology, Nature and Nature Communications.<ref name=\"auto3\">{{cite web |title=Dr. Rebecca D Jackson - Cancer Researcher at OSUCCC - James |url=https://cancer.osu.edu/research-and-education/find-a-researcher/search-researcher-directory/rebecca-d-jackson |website=The James - OSUCCC}}</ref>\n\nJackson's research is concentrated in the area of women's health, with a specific focus on defining clinical factors, biomarkers, and genetic associations for diseases that disproportionately affect women (particularly osteoporosis). Her laboratory has had continuous NIH funding for almost 30 years and she has authored or co-authored more than 250 peer-reviewed manuscripts, including the landmark Women's Health Initiative Calcium Plus Vitamin D Trial.<ref name=\"auto1\"/> Her work focuses on the epidemiology of chronic disease in women, including cancer, osteoporosis, cardiovascular disease and osteoarthritis.<ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n\nJackson spends about thirty percent of her time as a clinician and seventy percent as a researcher.<ref name=\"auto\"/> She currently practices at the Center for Women's Health in Columbus, Ohio.<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n\n== Injury ==\nJackson had a spinal cord injury in the late 1970s and has used a wheelchair since then.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n== Notable achievements ==\nJackson's work in the field of medicine has resulted in a number of awards and honors:\n\n* 1978, American Medical Women's Association Award for Academic Excellence.\n* 1988, Disabled Professional Woman of the Year Award, Pilot Club\n* 1998, elected to Ohio Women's Hall of Fame\n* 2003, profiled in \"200 Women, 200 Years: Ohio Women of the Year\"<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n* 2008, elected as a Fellow of the [[American Association for the Advancement of Science]].\n* 2015, OSU Distinguished Scholar Award, one of Ohio University's highest research honours.<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jackson, Rebecca D.}}\n[[Category:American endocrinologists]]\n[[Category:American diabetologists]]\n[[Category:Ohio State University faculty]]\n[[Category:Ohio State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Scientists from Ohio]]\n[[Category:American people with disabilities]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the American Association for the Advancement of Science]]\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Scientists with disabilities]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Professor of endocrinology, diabetes and metabolism at Ohio State University}}\n'''Rebecca D. Jackson''' (born 1955) Is a medical researcher, medical practitioner and professor of [[endocrinology]], [[diabetes]] and [[metabolism]]. Her research has been significant in the understanding and treatment of osteoporosis.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web |title=biography - Rebecca Jackson, MD (Ohio) |url=https://wayback.archive-it.org/org-350/20190508153453/https://www.nlm.nih.gov/exhibition/locallegends/Biographies/Jackson_Rebecca.html |website=wayback.archive-it.org}}</ref>\n\nJackson is director of the Center for Women's Health, the founding director of the [[Ohio State University]] Center for Clinical and Translational Science, associate dean for Clinical and Translational Research, and professor of Endocrinology, Diabetes, and Metabolism at the Ohio State University.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web |title=Rebecca D. Jackson, M.D. |url=https://prevention.nih.gov/research-priorities/research-needs-and-gaps/pathways-prevention/appropriate-use-drug-therapies-osteoporotic-fracture-prevention/workshop-agenda/rebecca-d-jackson-md |website=Office of Disease Prevention |language=en}}</ref> In 2008, she was elected as a Fellow of the [[American Association for the Advancement of Science]] and received the OSU Distinguished Scholar Award, one of Ohio University's highest research honours, in 2015.\n\n== Education ==\nJackson received her medical degree from Ohio State University College of Medicine in 1978.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite web|url=https://wexnermedical.osu.edu/find-a-doctor/rebecca-jackson-md-1315|title=Rebecca Jackson|website=wexnermedical.osu.edu}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nJackson was involved in one of the first studies to show that weight lifting rather than walking was more beneficial to maintaining bone density: that the ideal exercise to stimulate bone formation is force rather than repetition. She and her colleagues have also been involved in one of the landmark studies examining bisphosphonates, a new class of medications for treating postmenopausal osteoporosis.<ref name=\"auto\"/> She has co-authored hundreds of articles that have appeared in such well-respected publications as American Journal of Preventive Medicine, Arthritis & Rheumatology, Nature and Nature Communications.<ref name=\"auto3\">{{cite web |title=Dr. Rebecca D Jackson - Cancer Researcher at OSUCCC - James |url=https://cancer.osu.edu/research-and-education/find-a-researcher/search-researcher-directory/rebecca-d-jackson |website=The James - OSUCCC}}</ref>\n\nJackson's research is concentrated in the area of women's health, with a specific focus on defining clinical factors, biomarkers, and genetic associations for diseases that disproportionately affect women (particularly osteoporosis). Her laboratory has had continuous NIH funding for almost 30 years and she has authored or co-authored more than 250 peer-reviewed manuscripts, including the landmark Women's Health Initiative Calcium Plus Vitamin D Trial.<ref name=\"auto1\"/> Her work focuses on the epidemiology of chronic disease in women, including cancer, osteoporosis, cardiovascular disease and osteoarthritis.<ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n\nJackson spends about thirty percent of her time as a clinician and seventy percent as a researcher.<ref name=\"auto\"/> She currently practices at the Center for Women's Health in Columbus, Ohio.<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n\n== Injury ==\nJackson suffered a spinal cord injury in the late 1970s and has used a wheelchair since then.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n== Notable achievements ==\nJackson's work in the field of medicine has resulted in a number of awards and honors:\n\n* 1978, American Medical Women's Association Award for Academic Excellence.\n* 1988, Disabled Professional Woman of the Year Award, Pilot Club\n* 1998, elected to Ohio Women's Hall of Fame\n* 2003, profiled in \"200 Women, 200 Years: Ohio Women of the Year\"<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n* 2008, elected as a Fellow of the [[American Association for the Advancement of Science]].\n* 2015, OSU Distinguished Scholar Award, one of Ohio University's highest research honours.<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jackson, Rebecca D.}}\n[[Category:American endocrinologists]]\n[[Category:American diabetologists]]\n[[Category:Ohio State University faculty]]\n[[Category:Ohio State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Scientists from Ohio]]\n[[Category:American people with disabilities]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the American Association for the Advancement of Science]]\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Scientists with disabilities]]\n", "name_user": "Bcerrato1", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eInjury:removed \"suffered\"", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rebecca_D._Jackson"}
